Deputy Secretary (WHO) and Programme Manager for Tobacco Control National Tobacco Control Cell (NTCC) Ministry of Health & Family Welfare Govt. of Bangladesh.
The National Tobacco Control Cell (NTCC) has been established in March 2007 under the auspices of the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (MOHFW) with the objective of coordinating and implementing national policy and plan of action for tobacco control activities in Bangladesh. Its task is to curb tobacco use in Bangladesh through steering all tobacco control activities in the country by government non-government and international organizations. It is headed by the Joint Secretary (Public Health and WHO) of MOHFW. Day-to-day supervision is being done by coordinator of the cell the Deputy Secretary (WHO) of MOHFW.
A National Task Force to implement the Smoking and Usage of Tobacco Product (Control) Law 2005 was established by the MOHFW and is operational since 2007. The task force comprises of senior level representatives from the majority of government ministries. In addition to these the following government agencies and civil organizations are represented: National Board of Revenue Narcotics Control Department WHO Bangladesh Medical Association Bangladesh Medical and Dental Council Bangladesh Bar Council National Press Club National Cancer Research Institute and Hospital National Institute of Heart Disease and Hospital Bangladesh Anti-Tobacco Alliance and the Tobacco Control Organization. 
The executive order establishing the task force also identifies its duties including measures to: 
o	attain the objectives of the 2005 Act;
o	formulate guidelines to reduce tobacco use;
o	develop regulations concerning areas covered by legislation;
o	improve public awareness on the effects of tobacco use and tobacco control measures taken;
o	conduct research and surveys;
o	evaluate reports on the content of tobacco products as provided by importers;
o	arrange for training programmes on tobacco control for government and non-government officials;
o	oversee the programmes run by the National Tobacco Control Cell (see later);
o	help tobacco growers to shift to alternative crops;
o	prevent deleterious environmental impact of tobacco cultivation;
o	identify financial resources for tobacco control;
o	co-opt new members if necessary.
District and sub district (upazila) task forces have also been called upon with their spheres of duties described in the Strategic Plan. They should coordinate the implementation of the 2005 Act at their levels and report back to the National Tobacco Control Cell.

